In a statement, the vehicle manufacturer says due to this most of Toyota's best sellers suffered stock shortages in May. The plant suffered flood damage after the first floods in April. Senior Vice President of Sales and Marketing at Toyota South Africa Motors, Leon Theron, said the automobile manufacturer is content to have held onto the market leader position for another month since the temporary closure of the Durban plant in April. He said the recovery process at the Prospecton Plant remains on track but that a resumption date for operations is yet to be determined. Torrential rains killed 435 people in the KwaZulu-Natal province in April.  --SABC--